	<article class="post-107 post type-post status-publish hentry category-qa" id="post-107">
	<header class="postHeader">
				<div class="postKicker">
					</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Gail Collins Responds to Readers: Congress Versus Hobbit</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
							</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-06-10T17:07:31+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">June 10, 2014 1:07 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">June 10, 2014 1:07 pm</span>		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//collins.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/06/10/gail-collins-responds-to-readers-congress-versus-hobbit/" data-title="Gail Collins Responds to Readers: Congress Versus Hobbit" data-description="The Op-Ed columnist answered a few questions posed by commenters about her latest column, Congress Versus Hobbit.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Gail Collins, Op-Ed columnist, answered a few questions posed by commenters about her latest column, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/06/07/opinion/collins-congress-versus-hobbit.html">Congress Versus Hobbit</a>.</em></p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/06/07/opinion/collins-congress-versus-hobbit.html#permid=11973826"><b>Mayngram</b>, Monterey, Calif.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What our nation needs is a made for TV âReality Showâ on tax reform &#8230; after all, the one that&#8217;s playing in D.C. has demonstrated the viability of the concept simply by how long itâs been running.</p>
<div class="q left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Gail Collins:</b> Thanks to Mayngram and others who wrote in to suggest that Congress somehow be turned into a reality TV show. The idea of leaving them on an island for a few months was particularly seductive. I was also taken by the proposal to create a legislative version of âThe Bachelorette.â Maybe Republicans could propose amendments to an upcoming bill. Then Majority Leader Harry Reid would walk down the line of eager sponsors and hand out a rose to the happy winner.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">So many advantages. The Republicans would stop holding everything up because their amendments werenât being considered. Weâd see a soaring national interest in the Senate calendar, particularly if the senators were allowed to invite Reid off to candlelight picnics on the beach to plead their case. Then, if weâre lucky, a finale with Ted Cruz weeping and waving his floribunda triumphantly.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/06/07/opinion/collins-congress-versus-hobbit.html#permid=11973695"><b>Sandra</b>, Boston, Mass.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In any other place and time, who wouldn&#8217;t fire the entire lot of them?</p>
<div class="q left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Gail Collins: </b>Sandra, I always appreciate the opportunity to point out that things have been worse. Although itâs a little disheartening to realize how often I return defensively to the time before the Civil War <a href="//www.ushistory.org/us/31e.asp">that a representative from South Carolina beat a senator from Massachusetts half to death with his cane</a>.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/06/07/opinion/collins-congress-versus-hobbit.html#permid=11973603"><b>hm1342 </b>, N.C.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Truly, Gail, only Republicans are botching the tax code? No one in Washington is serious about tax reform, except for the special interest groups. They all want tax reform for their particular interest. And those groups are represented by lobbyists who always find ways of convincing the right politicians that their particular tax reform will benefit the national economy (and the politician&#8217;s next campaign). Is it any wonder why the federal tax code is a joke? Isn&#8217;t this reason enough to get a lot of this power out of our nation&#8217;s capital and back to the states?</p>
<div class="q left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Gail Collins:</b> Everybody who wants to put more power in state legislatures should be required to spend at least one session in a state capitol, watching the action. Wasnât North Carolina the one that passed a big anti-abortion law this year as an amendment to a bill on motorcycle safety? Iâm not trying to pick on your state â when it comes to places I would not want to have control of the federal tax code, the New York legislature would be very close to the top of the list. Just saying.</p>
	</div>
